class Solution {
    public int alternateDigitSum(int n) {
        int sum = 0;
        while (n != 0) {
            int digit = n % 10;
            sum += (digit % 2 == 0 ? 1 : -1) * digit;
            n /= 10;
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(n))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution iterates through the digits of the number n using a while loop. For each digit, it calculates the sign based on its position in the number (even or odd) and multiplies it with the digit. The sign is determined by checking if the remainder of dividing the digit by 2 is 0 or not. After calculating the sum, the algorithm updates n by dividing it by 10 to remove the last digit. This process continues until n becomes 0, at which point the sum is returned. The time complexity is O(log(n)) due to the iterative approach, and the space complexity is O(1) as the algorithm uses a constant amount of space. The energy implications are low as the algorithm does not involve any resource-intensive operations.

